Amanda Khoza, News24Police Minister Nathi Nhleko. (Jenni Evans, News24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Durban - Police Minister Nathi Nhleko on Tuesday said he was considering taking legal action after a Facebook account was set up in his name.The account, under Nhleko&rsquo;s full names, Nkosinathi Nhleko, had pictures of him with police officers. It appeared to have been removed.&ldquo;I wish to categorically distance myself from the Facebook account and regard the fraudulent use of my name and pictures as a serious violation of my individual rights. This act must be condemned in the strongest terms possible. For the record, I have never been on social media and have no intention to do so in the near future.&rdquo;Nhleko said he would not take the matter lightly. The incident should serve as a warning to all South Africans about the dark world of internet fraud and increases in cybercrimes globally, he said.READ: Zuckerberg says fake news on Facebook didn't sway election24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.